    <h2 id="how-much-space-do-plants-need">How Much Space Do Plants Need?</h2>
    <p>
      Every plant has two spacing requirements: <strong>in-row spacing</strong> (the gap between individual plants within a single row) and <strong>between-row spacing</strong> (the gap from one row to the next). Both numbers come from how large the plant grows at maturity — roots competing underground, leaves competing for light above, and air movement between plants that slows down fungal disease.
    </p>
    <figure class="my-6 float-right ml-6 w-48 sm:w-64">
      <img
        src="/plant-spacing-calculator-garden-grid.svg"
        alt="Vegetables planted in a grid pattern showing proper spacing between rows"
        width="400"
        height="300"
        loading="lazy"
        class="rounded-xl border border-moss-100 bg-moss-50/30"
      />
      <figcaption class="mt-2 text-xs text-bark-500">
        Proper grid spacing between vegetable rows improves airflow and reduces disease pressure.
      </figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      Airflow matters more than most gardeners realize. Crowded plants create humid microclimates that accelerate powdery mildew, blight, and other fungal diseases. Proper spacing lets air circulate around leaves, drying them faster after rain or irrigation. This is why tomatoes at 24&ndash;36 inches apart dramatically outperform tomatoes crammed at 12 inches, even in the same soil.
    </p>
    <p>
      Competition for nutrients and root space is the other factor. Tightly packed plants fight for the same water and mineral supply, resulting in smaller yields from every plant. It&rsquo;s almost always better to plant fewer, well-spaced plants than to fill every inch of bed and have all of them underperform.
    </p>
    <p>
      Square foot gardening uses a slightly different framework: each plant is assigned a square-foot block (e.g., 1 sq ft for a pepper, 4 sq ft for a tomato), and the bed is treated as a grid. This simplifies planning but uses the same underlying principle &mdash; each plant gets the area it needs at maturity.
    </p>
    <p>
      Raised beds change the equation, too. Because you never walk on the soil in a raised bed, it never compacts the way a traditional row garden does &mdash; roots can spread more freely in every direction instead of being blocked by dense, foot-trafficked soil between rows. That&rsquo;s why raised beds typically support <strong>20&ndash;30% tighter spacing</strong> than the same crop in a traditional row garden, and sometimes more for the most space-hungry crops. Tomatoes are the clearest example: spaced 36 inches apart between rows in a traditional garden, they can often go down to <strong>24 inches</strong> in a well-built raised bed. The spacing chart below reflects standard row-garden and square-foot-gardening figures &mdash; if you&rsquo;re working in a raised bed specifically, you can generally lean toward the tighter end of a crop&rsquo;s range.
    </p>

